The paper focuses on anomaly detection in e-commerce data using tensor decomposition, which is a common technique in machine learning and falls under the category of linear algebra. The use of Bayesian semi-supervised tensor decomposition and natural gradients suggests a focus on probabilistic modeling and optimization, which are common themes in the sub-categories of cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The paper also deals with data augmentation and optimization techniques, which are relevant to the sub-categories of cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) and cs.IT (Information Theory). Finally, the application of the method to e-commerce data suggests a potential fit with the sub-category of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms).
